<subSubSection id="02C66578FFFFFFBEFF3D987768907846" pageId="18" pageNumber="32" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="4A6336F3FFFFFFBEFF3D9877681C79C8" blockId="18.[151,756,1075,1319]" pageId="18" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis id="78A8EAE1FFFFFFBEFF3D98776805792A" bold="true" box="[151,264,1075,1099]" pageId="18" pageNumber="32">Remarks:</emphasis>
It is characterized by numerous chambers, not inflated, distinct and gradually increase in size as added, while the later chambers in many specimens are slightly decreasing.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4A6336F3FFFFFFBEFF3D98F568907846" blockId="18.[151,756,1075,1319]" pageId="18" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis id="78A8EAE1FFFFFFBEFF3D98F568D879A8" bold="true" box="[151,469,1201,1225]" pageId="18" pageNumber="32">Stratigraphic distribution:</emphasis>
It is recorded in the Cretaceous of 
<collectingCountry id="32CB7663FFFFFFBEFE98989468807989" box="[306,397,1232,1256]" name="Trinidad and Tobago" pageId="18" pageNumber="32">Trinidad</collectingCountry>
(CUSHMAN, 1946). It is recorded in the Maastrichtian and rarely found in the Paleocene of the Esh El Mallaha area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
